<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-30T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="54" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00112 Wood Pulp/28:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-01T00:00:00+01:00">July
                                        1, 1940—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received July 1—8:08
                                    p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1920. Your 1042, May 30 [<hi rend="italic">31</hi>], 4 p.m. Letter
                                received today from Foreign Office refers to Lord Halifax’s
                                statement that there would be no difficulty from British point of
                                view in passage of Swedish vessels engaged in Swedish-American trade
                                and in particular to outward voyage of four vessels loading wood
                                pulp for the United States (my 1494, June 3, 11 p.m.). Foreign
                                Office states that German Government, however, has definitely
                                refused to allow Swedish ships to trade outside the Baltic and in
                                view of this attitude there is nothing the British can do to
                                help.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>